'''Beatrice Sylvia Vianen''' (born 6 November 1935 in [[Paramaribo]]) is a Surinamese writer who goes by the name '''Bea Vianen'''.<ref>[http://www.dbnl.org/auteurs/auteur.php?id=vian001 Bea Vianen in the Digitale Bibliotheek Nederlandse Letteren (Dutch)]</ref> She is of both [[Afro-Surinamese|African]] and [[Indo-Surinamese|Indian]] ancestry and spent time in the [[Netherlands]] starting in 1957. She writes mainly in [[Dutch language|Dutch]], but occasionally in [[Sranan Tongo]]. Her first novel was '''''Sarnami, Hai''''' or "Surinam I am" in 1969. She is an admirer of the Trinidadian novelist [[V. S. Naipaul]].<ref name="Wilson1991">{{cite book|author=Katharina M. Wilson|title=An Encyclopedia of Continental Women Writers|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ncN7uneLKrcC&pg=PA1299|year=1991|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-8240-8547-6|page=1299}}</ref>
