{{Infobox person | name = Philippe de Tarrazi | image = Tarazani.jpg | image_size = 170px | movement = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1865|04|28}} | birth_place = [[Beirut]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1956|08|07|1865|04|28 }} | death_place = [[Beirut]], [[Lebanon]] | occupation = }} [[Viscount]] '''Philippe de Tarrazi''' ({{lang-ar|فيليب دي طرّازي}} / [[ALA-LC]]: ''Fīlīb dī Ṭarrāzī''; 28 April 1865 – 7 August 1956), was a [[Lebanon|Lebanese]] [[polymath]], [[philanthropist]], founder of the [[National Library of Lebanon]] and a founding member of the [[Arab Academy of Damascus]].
== Life == Philippe was born in Beirut to a renowned [[Syriac Catholic Church|Syriac Catholic]] merchant family which had recently emigrated from [[Aleppo]]. His father was given the honorary title [[viscount]] by [[Pope Leo XIII]], which he later held. He studied at the patriarchal school and later the [[Collège Notre Dame de Jamhour|Jesuit College]]. Philippe showed interest in the [[Syriac literature|Syriac]], [[Arabic literature|Arabic]] and [[French literature|French]] literatures, and authored at least 57 books on these, of which only 25 were published.
De Tarrazi helped victims of the [[First World War]].<ref name="Gorgias">{{cite web | url=http://www.gorgiaspress.com/bookshop/pc-55975-16-de-tarrazi-philip-catalogue-of-eastern-and-western-arabic-libraries.aspx | title=de Tarrazi, Philip. Catalogue of Eastern and Western Arabic Libraries | publisher=Gorgias Press | accessdate=September 23, 2012}}</ref> He was active in Lebanese [[Phoenicianism|Phoenicianist]] cultural circles and was also close to the [[Assyrian nationalism|Assyrian nationalist]] [[Naum Faiq]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=0d1SnaKLQ9QC&pg=PA138&dq=philippe+de+tarrazi&hl=fr&ei=g9_OTc2_JIHpOfKN8ZIN&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&ved=0CCoQ6AEwADge#v=onepage&q=philippe%20de%20tarrazi&f=false Reviving Phoenicia: in search of identity in Lebanon, Asher Kaufman]</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.aramaic-dem.org/Arabic/Tarikh_Skafe/Naoum_Fayeq/De-Tarrazzi-1.htm | script-title=ar:كلمات و أقوال في الفقيد الملفونو نعوم فائق، المؤرخ السرياني الفكونت فيليب دي طرازي | publisher=Aramaic Democratic Movement | accessdate=September 23, 2012|language=ar}}</ref>
De Tarrazi was an avid collector of books and publications. His library included an extensive collection of publication from the Near East.
==Legacy== The [[Lebanese National Library]] was established in 1921, with a donation from Viscount de Tarrazi of twenty thousand books, many rare manuscripts, and the first issues of newspapers from the [[Near East]].<ref name="Manguel p302">{{citation |title=The Library at Night |last=Manguel |first=Alberto |authorlink=Alberto Manguel |publisher=[[Yale University Press]] |location=New Haven & London |year=2006 |isbn=978-0-300-13914-3 |page=302}}.</ref> De Tarazi's instructions were that his donation should form "the core of what should become the Great Library of [[Beirut|Beyrouth]]."<ref name="Manguel p302" /> It was placed under the supervision of the Ministry of National Education in 1922.<ref name="Wedgeworth p452">{{citation |title=World Encyclopedia of Library and Information Services |last=Wedgeworth |first=Robert |publisher=[[American Library Association|ALA Editions]] |year=1993 |isbn=0-8389-0609-5 |page=452}}.</ref> It moved to the [[Parliament of Lebanon#The building|Lebanese Parliament building]] in 1937.<ref name="Wedgeworth p452" />
